    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Back on Their Feet</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Caroline Birenbaum letter on September 3 article holds real advantage will come when rollator--walker with wheels--can be used to navigate steps (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Trying Out a Different Set of Wheels'' (Seniority, Sept. 3), which discussed the benefits of the rollator -- a walker with wheels that can help people regain mobility.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Trying Out a Different Set of Wheels'' (Seniority, Sept. 3), which discussed the benefits of the rollator -- a walker with wheels that can help people regain mobility.</p>
        <p>I come from a long line of urban walkers -- the human variety. Years ago, when I set out to order a rollator for an aunt, I asked how she might use it to navigate the steps outside her building and inside her lobby. I was advised that rollators were designed for flat surfaces. If this limitation is overcome, such devices will be a godsend for more people.</p>
        <p>One place where rollators would be effective is museums. Making rollators available there for practical ''test drives'' would be good marketing, too.</p>
        <p>CAROLINE BIRENBAUM  Larchmont, N.Y., Sept. 4</p>
      </block>
